gested interpretation to\nmean \'are born in lower species.\' See _Kh_ andogya, p. 585, and Maitri, p.\n211, about asuras or demons. It is interesting to note that in the\nIntroduction to the Mahabhashya, there is an allusion to a story of the\n\'demons\' being \'vanquished\' in consequence of their grammatical blunders.\n\n[153:1](sbe0823.htm#fr_627) Those deluded by worldly objects; \'this\' means\n\'heedlessness.\'\n\n[153:2](sbe0823.htm#fr_628) _S_ a _n_ kara cites a stanza from Manu, which\nsays that king Yama Vaivasvata dwells in the heart of every one. Cf. Aitareya-\nupanishad, p. 187. The following clause he understands to contain two epithets\nof Yama, meaning \'immortal, and intent on the Brahman.\' I follow Nilaka _nth_\na, but not very confidently.\n\n[153:3](sbe0823.htm#fr_629) Here we have the developments, the varying forms,\nof death or heedlessness.\n\n[153:4](sbe0823.htm#fr_630) Cf. Gita, [p. 57](sbe0805.htm#page_57). I. e.\npaths contrary to _S_ rutis and _S_ m _ri_ tis.\n\n[153:5](sbe0823.htm#fr_631) Concentration of mind on the self or Brahman.\n\n[153:6](sbe0823.htm#fr_632) I. e. the egoism spoken of before.\n\n[153:7](sbe0823.htm#fr_633) I. e. to this mortal world. Cf. Gita, [p.\n84](sbe0811.htm#page_84), and B _ri_ hadara _n_ yaka, pp. 855, 856. There =\nfrom the next world. _S_ a _n_ kara says, \'having lived there.\'\n\n[153:8](sbe0823.htm#fr_634) I.e. the senses. Cf. Gita, [p.\n123](sbe0820.htm#page_123), and inter alia \xc3\x8e _s_ opanishad, p. 10.\n\n[153:9](sbe0823.htm#fr_635) Cf. Ka _th_ a, p. 129, and B _ri_ hadara _n_ yaka,\np. 889.\n\n[153:10](sbe0823.htm#fr_636) I. e. the fruit. Cf. Ka _th_ a, p. 155, and Mu\n_nd_ aka, p. 317.\n\n[154:1](sbe0823.htm#fr_637) I. e. its identity with the Brahman.\n\n[154:2](sbe0823.htm#fr_638) I. e. in various forms of life, Nilaka _nth_ a.\n\n[154:3](sbe0823.htm#fr_639) The going about in search of enjoyments.\n\n[154:4](sbe0823.htm#fr_640) The contact leads to pondering on them, and that\nto desire