 the purpose of its existence, and what\nmisery does it undergo on entering the course of worldly life?\n\n[157:2](sbe0823.htm#fr_667) \'The danger,\' says _S_ a _n_ kara, \'is that of\ncontravening Vedic texts such as "I am the Brahman," "Thou art that," &c.\' May\nit not rather be that pointed out at Ka _th_ opanishad, p. 129, viz. never\nattaining final emancipation? Cf. also N _ri_ si _m_ ha Tapini, p. 223.\n\n[157:3](sbe0823.htm#fr_668) The individual selfs, _S_ a _n_ kara.\n\n[157:4](sbe0823.htm#fr_671) Nature or maya.\n\n[157:5](sbe0823.htm#fr_670) The appearance of degradation to an inferior state\nbeing delusive.\n\n[157:6](sbe0823.htm#fr_672) The original word implies the possession of ai _s_\nvarya, dharma, ya _s_ as, _s_ ri, vairagya, moksha. See _S_ veta _s_ vatara,\np. 329 (where the list is slightly different). For another definition, see\nMaitri, p. 6 (gloss).\n\n[157:7](sbe0823.htm#fr_673) See note , p. 156.\n\n[157:8](sbe0823.htm#fr_674) _S_ a _n_ kara says: \'The question of Dh _ri_\ntarash _t_ ra having suggested a difference between two principles, one of\nwhich constrains, and the other of which is constrained, the answer is--Such a\ndifference ought not to be alleged, as it involves "danger." Then the question\narises, How is the difference, which does appear to be explained? The reply\nis, It is due to the beginningless principle--delusion or ignorance. The next\nsentence shows that the universe as it appears is also a result of delusion.\'\nNilaka _nth_ a says expressly, changes = delusion. He renders the original\nwhich we have translated by \'beginningless\' first, to mean \'collection of\nobjects of enjoyments.\' _S_ a _n_ kara\'s explanation seems tautological as\nregards the words \'connexion with the beginningless,\' which occur twice in the\nabove. Nilaka _nth_ a\'s p. 158 is not quite clear. May the expression on the\nsecond occasion mean, that the connexion by which beings are stated before to\nexist has had no beginning--has existed from eternity? The translation should\nthen run thus: \'And beings exist by a connexion which had no beginning;\' (see\nSariraka Bhashya, p. 494.) Connexions of things = creation of universe by his\npower.\n\n[158:1](sbe0823.htm#fr_675) E. g. Agnish _t_ oma, &c., _S_ a _n_ kara.\n\n[158:2](sbe0823.htm#fr_676) I. e. impiety or piety, sin or merit.\n\n[158:3](sbe0823.htm#fr_679) In _S_ rutis and Sm _ri_ tis, which _S_ a _n_ kara\nquotes. _Kh_ andogya, p. 622; Mu _nd_ aka, p. 309; B _ri_ hadara _n_ yaka, p.\n911. See, too, Maitri, p. 131.\n\n[158:4](sbe0823.htm#fr_678) Of the man devoid of knowledge.\n\n[158:5](sbe0823.htm#fr_680) Cf. Gita, [p. 76](sbe0809.htm#page_76), and B _ri_\nhadara _n_ yaka, p. 636.\n\n[158:6](sbe0823.htm#fr_681) See [p. 164](sbe0824.htm#page_164), note\n[9](sbe0824.htm#fn_726) infra.\n\n[158:7](sbe0823.htm#fr_682) The feeling of one\'s own superiority over others\nin piety.\n\n[158:8](sbe0823.htm#fr_683) In the shape of Nakshatras,\' says _S_ a _n_ kara,\nwhich is not quite intelligible. See _Kh_ andogya, p. 258, and Anugita infra,\n[p. 240](sbe0829.htm#page_240).\n\n[159:1](sbe0823.htm#fr_684) According to the Vedantic theory, the acts of\npiety purify the inner man, and are thus a stepping-stone to knowledge. See\nIntroduction, [p. 147](sbe0821.htm#page_147) supra. Cf. Gita, [p.\n122](sbe0820.htm#page_122); and B _ri_ hadara _n_ yaka, p. 899.\n\n[159:2](sbe0823.htm#fr_685) I. e. physical, mental, and such as is caused by\nsuperhuman agency. This is _S_ a _n_ kara\'s explanation. It is somewhat far\nfetched, but I can find none better. Cf. Gita, [p. 49](sbe0804.htm#page_49).\nAnd see also B _ri_ hadara _n_ yaka, p. 876, and the commentary of _S_ a _n_\nkara there with \xc3\x82nandagiri\'s gloss.\n\n[159:3](sbe0823.htm#fr_686) E. g. wife, children, &c.\n\n[159:4](sbe0823.htm#fr_687) I. e. vexed as to how his livelihood is to be\nearned, &c.\n\n[159:5](sbe0823.htm#fr_688) Excess, e.g. too much obsequiousness towards a\n\'taciturn man,\' owing to his holiness, &c. Taciturn man = ascetic. Injury =\ndisrespect, &c. Perhaps the protest against worldliness is here carried to an\nextreme. _S_ a _n_ kara cites Manu as a parallel, \'A Brahma _n_ a should be\nafraid of (worldly) respect as of poison.\'\n\n[159:6](sbe0823.htm#fr_689) E.g. the Ku _s_ a grass, deerskin, &c., mentioned\nat Gita, [p. 68](sbe0808.htm#page_68).\n\n[159:7](sbe0823.htm#fr_690) I. e. he should not parade his actions. _S_ a _n_\nkara compares Vasish _th_ a and a Vedic text. See, too, the quotation at\nTaitt. \xc3\x82ra _n_. p. 902.\n\n[160:1](sbe0823.htm#fr_691) Cf. Gita, [p. 103](sbe0815.htm#page_103). _S_ a\n_n_ kara suggests an alternative explanation of this stanza, which will make\nit mean that one performing the operations of the senses, should devote\noneself nevertheless to the unknown principle, and not consider the senses to\nbe the self.\n\n[160:2](sbe0823.htm#fr_692) I. e. beyond the reach of inference; \'subtle,\'\nsays _S_ a _n_ kara. Cf. _S_ veta _s_ vatara, p. 364; B _ri_ hadara _n_ yaka,\np. 855; Maitri, p. 182; and Ka _th_ a, p. 149, where _S_ a _n_ kara suggests a\nsomewhat different meaning. As to immovable, cf. \xc3\x8e _s_ a, p. 10, and Gita, [p.\n104](sbe0815.htm#page_104). _S_ a _n_ kara renders it by \'void of activity;\'\nand pure he paraphrases by \'free from ignorance and other taints.\'\n\n[160:3](sbe0823.htm#fr_693) It is difficult to say what \'in this way\' refers\nto. _S_ a _n_ kara renders it by \'as possessing qualities appertaining to the\ntwo kinds of body.\' On _S_ a _n_ kara\'s suggested meaning of the stanza\npreceding (see note  1), it would refer to the confusion of the senses with\nthe self.\n\n[160:4](sbe0823.htm#fr_694) Such a person is called a destroyer of his own\nself at \xc3\x8e _s_ opanishad, p. 9.\n\n[160:5](sbe0823.htm#fr_695) I. e. by the troubles of worldly life.\n\n[160:6](sbe0823.htm#fr_696) Cf. \'without belongings\' at Gita, [p.\n128](sbe0820.htm#page_128).\n\n[160:7](sbe0823.htm#fr_697) Anger and other obstacles to concentration of\nmind.\n\n[160:8](sbe0823.htm#fr_698) I. e. unintelligent. The text of Vasish _th_ a\nreferred to in note  7, p. 159, says he should act like an unintelligent man.\nCf. also Gau _d_ apada-karikas, p. 443, and _S_ ariraka Bhashya, p. 1041.\n\n[160:9](sbe0823.htm#fr_699) I. e. singing the praises of their own greatness\nand worth, instead of keeping their \'conduct unknown.\'\n\n[161:1](sbe0823.htm#fr_700) Highly esteemed for or strongly attached to, _S_ a\n_n_ kara. Human wealth = wife, offspring, property, &c. Cf. _Kh_ andogya, p.\n319; B _ri_ hadara _n_ yaka, p. 262.\n\n[161:2](sbe0823.htm#fr_701) I. e. veracity and other duties taught by the\nVedas.\n\n[161:3](sbe0823.htm#fr_702) \'They need fear nought,\' says Nilaka _nth_ a.\n\n[161:4](sbe0823.htm#fr_703) I. e. may sacrifice to them, _S_ a _n_ kara.\n\n[161:5](sbe0823.htm#fr_704) Not even the deity to whom the sacrifice is\noffered is equal to one who knows the Brahman. Cf. Taittiriya, p. 23, and.\nAnugita, [p. 250](sbe0831.htm#page_250).\n\n[161:6](sbe0823.htm#fr_705) I. e. one who is \'taciturn\' and does not parade\nhis greatness.\n\n[161:7](sbe0823.htm#fr_706) He does not care for the respect shown him.\n\n[161:8](sbe0823.htm#fr_707) Because he knows the Brahman.\n\n[161:9](sbe0823.htm#fr_708) I. e. restraint of all senses, not of speech only.\nFor the contrast compare that between _s_ reya and preya at Ka _th_ a, p. 92.\n\n[161:10](sbe0823.htm#fr_709) I. e. by all men of understanding. _S_ a _n_\nkara\'s rendering is different: \'The next, which is known as Tad, is for\ntaciturnity.\' He cites for this Gita, [p. 120](sbe0819.htm#page_120).\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: Chapter III](sbe0824.htm)\n\n'